---
import SiteHeader from "../components/SiteHeader.astro";
import SiteMeta from "../components/SiteMeta.astro";
import "../styles/global.css";
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <SiteMeta
      title="About | Lindwurm Herald"
      description="The story behind Lindwurm Herald, an independent chronicle dedicated to the world of Warcrow."
    />
  </head>
  <body>
    <SiteHeader />

    <main class="about-page">
      <section class="about-panel">
        <div class="about-copy">
          <p class="kicker">About</p>
          <h1>About Lindwurm Herald</h1>

          <p>In Lindwurm, wars do not begin when blades are drawn.</p>

          <p>
            They begin much earlier: in a rumour whispered across a tavern table, in a sealed letter that
            never reaches its destination, in the quiet movement of a patrol beyond the border.
          </p>

          <p>Lindwurm Herald was born to follow that trail.</p>

          <p>
            We are an independent chronicle dedicated to the world of Warcrow: its factions, conflicts,
            characters, armies, and the stories written between mist, blood, and orichalcum. Here you will
            find news, analysis, rumours, reports, and observations from the roads of Lindwurm, not as
            simple announcements, but as fragments of a living world shaped by every battle.
          </p>
        </div>

        <figure class="about-figure about-figure-portrait">
          <img src="/images/aldren-vael-portrait.png" alt="Aldren Vael, chronicler of Lindwurm Herald" />
        </figure>

        <div class="about-copy">
          <p>
            The voice behind the Herald is Aldren Vael, a human born on the borderlands of the Hegemony of
            Embersig. For years, he served as a campaign scribe, military messenger, and field chronicler,
            following expeditions, recording troop movements, and archiving reports few were ever meant to
            read.
          </p>

          <p>
            It was there that he learned an uncomfortable truth: in war, history rarely belongs to those
            who live it. It belongs to those who survive long enough to tell it, or to those powerful
            enough to rewrite it.
          </p>

          <p>
            Aldren saw reports corrected before they were sent, defeats reshaped into noble sacrifices,
            disappearances reduced to footnotes, and victories polished until they barely resembled the
            truth. In time, he left the official seals of Embersig behind and took to the road.
          </p>
        </div>

        <figure class="about-figure about-figure-miniature">
          <img src="/images/aldren-vael-miniature.png" alt="Aldren Vael miniature on a scenic base" />
        </figure>

        <div class="about-copy">
          <p>
            Now he travels across Lindwurm as an independent chronicler, gathering testimonies from
            soldiers, merchants, scouts, spellcasters, nobles, deserters, and creatures no imperial archive
            would admit to hearing. His emblem, a weathered compass rose, represents what guides his craft:
            finding direction where others see only chaos.
          </p>

          <p>
            Lindwurm Herald does not promise perfect neutrality. No chronicler who has walked a battlefield
            could claim that without lying. But it does promise something harder: to look where others turn
            away, to preserve the names power tries to erase, and to tell the stories that survive from one
            campaign to the next.
          </p>

          <p>Because in Lindwurm, every faction has its banners.</p>

          <p>Every army has its heroes.</p>

          <p>Every nation has its version of the truth.</p>

          <p>The Herald has only one mission:</p>

          <p class="about-closing">to follow the trail of truth before the victors bury it.</p>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>
  </body>
</html>
